\name{plot.gsca_ridge}
\alias{plot.gsca_ridge}
\title{
Plot GSCA Results
}
\usage{
\method{plot}{gsca_ridge}(x, ...)
}
\arguments{
  \item{x}{An object of class "gsca_ridge" returned by \code{gsca_ridge()}}

  \item{...}{Additional arguments (not used)}
}
\value{
Invisible NULL
}
\description{
Creates a path diagram of the GSCA model following best practices for structural equation modeling visualization.
}
\details{
The function provides instructions for creating a publication-quality path diagram of the GSCA model.
While the function itself does not generate a graphical plot (as this typically requires additional
packages like DiagrammeR or semPlot), it outputs the necessary specifications and code templates
to create visualizations.

The output includes:
\itemize{
  \item{Structural model specification in R formula syntax}
  \item{Path coefficients with significance indicators when bootstrap results are available}
  \item{Instructions for using popular R packages to generate the actual plot}
}

When bootstrap results are available, significant paths (95\% CI not including zero) are marked
with an asterisk (*). The function serves as a bridge between the analytical results and
visualization tools, ensuring that the path diagram accurately reflects the model estimates
and their statistical significance.
}
\examples{
# Fit a GSCA model
results <- gsca_ridge(data, measurement_model, structural_model)

# Get plotting instructions
plot(results)

# For actual visualization, use external packages:
# library(DiagrammeR)
# Create diagram using the specifications provided by plot()
}
